Process management commands
******************************************
1.Show the all the running process in system

  command : ps -ef

  command : ps -ef | grep systemd

    ps-ef =shows all the running process
     (|)=pipe
     grep systemd=filtering only containing systemd

  command : ps -ef | grep systemd | grep -v grep
   
   >removes unwanted grep pipelines

2.Check the cpus&memory usage

  command : top

  >identify the zombie files

  command : ps -ef | grep z

  >identify the orphan 

   command : ps -ef | grep <ppid>

3.Runs a process for 100 seconds

  command : sleep 100
  
  exit :Ctrl+z

  sleep command is used to pause execuation for a specified amount of time

  example : sleep 5
   the terminal freeze for 5 seconds and then it return automatically

   >in shell scipt

   create a file : vi backup.sh
   #!/bin/bash
   echo "starting backup ...."
   sleep 10
   echo "backup completed"

   give the permissions: chmod +x backup.sh
   
   run script : ./backup.sh

   the terminator is freeze 10 seconds and then it return automatically  
  

4.Show your stopped process

  command : jobs

5.Background resume
  resume a stopped job and run it background

  command : bg %1

6. shows a detailed info about a specific process
  command : ps -fp <pid>

  example : ps -fp 982


7.Killing the process

 command : kill pid ---------->process id

 example : kill 1782

8.Forcefully stop a process

 command : kill -9 pid

 example : kill -9 1732


9.kill the process using process name instead of id

 command : pkill

 example : pkill sleep

10.Change priority of a running process command

 command : renice

 example : renice 10 -p 63590

  here : renice is used to change priority of running process

         10 --> new priority value

         -p --> process id

         0 is the normal priority , 10 is the lower priority, 19 is the very low priority.

11. View manage running process in real time 

 command : htop 

 if command is not found install epel --> extra package for enterprice linux

 Used to monitor:

-->CPU usage
-->Memory usage
-->Running processes
-->Process priority
-->Kill processes
    

